PRD: [Lisa]

1. Executive Summary
This document outlines the technical architecture and functional requirements for a **Linear Accelerator (Linac) Maintenance System**. The application is designed to manage the lifecycle of medical assets, track preventive maintenance (PM), log corrective actions (Work Orders), and facilitate communication between clinical staff (Radiographers) and technical staff (Engineers).

This is an internal app, you should investigate if we can just have the SQLite db in a shared drive where the employees can access
or we need to ask IT to give us a Virtual server hosting solution.

2. Technical Stack

Framework: TanStack Start (SSR + client)

Routing: TanStack Router (file-based)

State / Tables: TanStack Table

UI Components: shadcn/ui

Styling: Tailwind CSS v4

Database: SQLite (via better-sqlite3)

ORM: Drizzle ORM

Auth: Better Auth (Email/Password + MS Entra ID SSO)

Hosting Target: a Virtual server in the company network.



## 2. Data Model & Schema

The system relies on a relational SQLite database designed to support multi-system assets, volatile monitoring data, and complex maintenance histories.

### 2.1 Core Entity Definitions

| Entity | Description |
| --- | --- |
| **Assets** | The physical Linac units. Tracks static data (Serial No, Model) and lifecycle dates (Installation, Warranty, Customer Acceptance). |
| **Systems** | Functional subsystems of a Linac (e.g., Vacuum, RF, MLC, Imaging). Enables granular maintenance tracking. |
| **Asset_Systems** | A many-to-many junction table linking specific Linacs to their installed subsystems. |
| **Asset_Info** | Stores volatile, frequently changing data: HT hours, Magnetron/Thyratron installation dates, and days since last breakdown. |
| **PM_Tasks** | A master library of preventive maintenance steps, categorized by System and Interval (6/12/24 months). Includes manual references (`doc_section`). |
| **User_Requests** | Issues reported by clinical staff. Can exist independently or be attached to a Work Order. |
| **Work_Orders** | Records of corrective maintenance (breakdowns). Supports multiple engineers, multiple actions, and multi-day durations. |

### 2.2 Database Schema (SQLite via Drizzle)

```sql
-- I. Authentication & Authorization (Better-Auth + Entra ID)
CREATE TABLE user (id TEXT PRIMARY KEY, name TEXT NOT NULL, email TEXT NOT NULL UNIQUE, email_verified INTEGER NOT NULL, image TEXT, role TEXT DEFAULT 'user' NOT NULL, created_at DATETIME, updated_at DATETIME);
CREATE TABLE role_permissions (role TEXT NOT NULL, resource TEXT NOT NULL, action TEXT NOT NULL, PRIMARY KEY (role, resource, action));
CREATE TABLE session (id TEXT PRIMARY KEY, expires_at DATETIME NOT NULL, token TEXT NOT NULL UNIQUE, ip_address TEXT, user_agent TEXT, user_id TEXT NOT NULL, created_at DATETIME, updated_at DATETIME, FOREIGN KEY (user_id) REFERENCES user(id) ON DELETE CASCADE);
CREATE TABLE account (id TEXT PRIMARY KEY, account_id TEXT NOT NULL, provider_id TEXT NOT NULL, user_id TEXT NOT NULL, access_token TEXT, refresh_token TEXT, id_token TEXT, access_token_expires_at DATETIME, refresh_token_expires_at DATETIME, scope TEXT, password TEXT, created_at DATETIME, updated_at DATETIME, FOREIGN KEY (user_id) REFERENCES user(id) ON DELETE CASCADE);
CREATE TABLE verification (id TEXT PRIMARY KEY, identifier TEXT NOT NULL, value TEXT NOT NULL, expires_at DATETIME NOT NULL);

-- II. Administrative & Lookup Tables
CREATE TABLE sites (site_id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT, site_name TEXT NOT NULL UNIQUE, updated_at DATETIME, deleted_at DATETIME);
CREATE TABLE systems (system_id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT, system_name TEXT NOT NULL UNIQUE, updated_at DATETIME, deleted_at DATETIME);
CREATE TABLE engineers (engineer_id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT, first_name TEXT NOT NULL, last_name TEXT NOT NULL, user_id TEXT, updated_at DATETIME, deleted_at DATETIME, FOREIGN KEY (user_id) REFERENCES user(id));

-- III. Asset Inventory & Monitoring
CREATE TABLE asset_info (info_id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT, magnetron_date DATETIME, thyratron_date DATETIME, ht_hours REAL, days_since_breakdown INTEGER DEFAULT 0, updated_at DATETIME, deleted_at DATETIME);
CREATE TABLE assets (asset_id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT, serial_number TEXT NOT NULL UNIQUE, model_name TEXT, warranty_years INTEGER, cat_date DATETIME, installation_date DATETIME, status TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT 'Operational', site_id INTEGER, info_id INTEGER, updated_at DATETIME, deleted_at DATETIME, FOREIGN KEY (site_id) REFERENCES sites(site_id), FOREIGN KEY (info_id) REFERENCES asset_info(info_id));
CREATE TABLE asset_systems (asset_id INTEGER, system_id INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY (asset_id, system_id), FOREIGN KEY (asset_id) REFERENCES assets(asset_id), FOREIGN KEY (system_id) REFERENCES systems(system_id));

-- IV. Preventive Maintenance (PM)
CREATE TABLE pm_tasks (task_id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT, system_id INTEGER, instruction TEXT NOT NULL, doc_section TEXT, interval_months INTEGER NOT NULL, updated_at DATETIME, deleted_at DATETIME, FOREIGN KEY (system_id) REFERENCES systems(system_id));
CREATE TABLE asset_pm (pm_instance_id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT, asset_id INTEGER, engineer_id INTEGER, created_at DATETIME DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, completed_at DATETIME, updated_at DATETIME, deleted_at DATETIME, FOREIGN KEY (asset_id) REFERENCES assets(asset_id), FOREIGN KEY (engineer_id) REFERENCES engineers(engineer_id));
CREATE TABLE asset_pm_results (result_id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT, pm_instance_id INTEGER, task_id INTEGER, status TEXT NOT NULL, findings TEXT, updated_at DATETIME, deleted_at DATETIME, FOREIGN KEY (pm_instance_id) REFERENCES asset_pm(pm_instance_id), FOREIGN KEY (task_id) REFERENCES pm_tasks(task_id));

-- V. Corrective Maintenance (Work Orders & Requests)
CREATE TABLE user_requests (request_id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT, asset_id INTEGER, system_id INTEGER, reported_by TEXT NOT NULL, comment_text TEXT NOT NULL, status TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT 'Open', engineer_id INTEGER, created_at DATETIME DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, updated_at DATETIME, deleted_at DATETIME, FOREIGN KEY (asset_id) REFERENCES assets(asset_id), FOREIGN KEY (system_id) REFERENCES systems(system_id), FOREIGN KEY (engineer_id) REFERENCES engineers(engineer_id));
CREATE TABLE work_orders (wo_id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT, asset_id INTEGER, system_id INTEGER, description_of_fault TEXT NOT NULL, start_at DATETIME DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, end_at DATETIME, status TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT 'Open', updated_at DATETIME, deleted_at DATETIME, FOREIGN KEY (asset_id) REFERENCES assets(asset_id), FOREIGN KEY (system_id) REFERENCES systems(system_id));
CREATE TABLE work_order_requests (wo_id INTEGER, request_id INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY (wo_id, request_id), FOREIGN KEY (wo_id) REFERENCES work_orders(wo_id), FOREIGN KEY (request_id) REFERENCES user_requests(request_id));
CREATE TABLE work_order_engineers (wo_id INTEGER, engineer_id INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY (wo_id, engineer_id), FOREIGN KEY (wo_id) REFERENCES work_orders(wo_id), FOREIGN KEY (engineer_id) REFERENCES engineers(engineer_id));
```
